Yes — sha512 should be in the Sensu Asset definition.

A Sensu dynamic runtime asset build is made of:

url: <asset-tar.gz-url>
sha512: <checksum>
filters:
  - entity.system.os == 'linux'
  - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'

Sensu docs describe an asset build as the combination of an artifact URL, SHA512 checksum, and optional filters; Sensu downloads the artifact from the URL and only unpacks it if the downloaded file’s SHA512 matches the configured checksum. 

Where to get the asset tar file

You have 3 options.

Option 1 — From Bonsai asset definition

For public Sensu assets, Bonsai usually provides the asset tarball URL and SHA512 in the asset definition.

Example from Bonsai-style asset YAML:

spec:
  builds:
    - url: https://assets.bonsai.sensu.io/.../asset_linux_arm64.tar.gz
      sha512: <sha512>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'

Bonsai asset pages can include an “Asset definition” section with the url and sha512; for example, the sensu-plugins-http Bonsai page shows a tarball URL under assets.bonsai.sensu.io and its SHA512. 


---

Option 2 — Use sensuctl asset add to generate the definition

This is the easiest way.

Sensu docs say you can install an asset definition directly from Bonsai using:

sensuctl asset add <ASSET_NAME>:<ASSET_VERSION>

They also recommend pinning a version instead of using latest, because latest can introduce breaking changes. 

For your assets, run these in a scratch/dev Sensu backend, not directly in GitOps-managed STG if you want to avoid ArgoCD drift:

sensuctl asset add sensu/http-checks:<version> --rename http-check
sensuctl asset add sensu/sensu-aggregate-check:<version> --rename aggregate-check
sensuctl asset add sensu/sensu-aws-sns-handler:<version> --rename aws-sns-handler
sensuctl asset add sensu/sensu-cloudwatch-check:<version> --rename cloudwatch-check
sensuctl asset add sensu-plugins/sensu-plugins-aws:<version> --rename plugins-aws
sensuctl asset add sensu-plugins/sensu-plugins-http:<version> --rename plugins-http
sensuctl asset add sensu/sensu-ruby-runtime:<version> --rename ruby-runtime

Then export the generated asset YAML:

sensuctl asset list --format yaml > generated-assets.yaml

From that file, copy the url, sha512, and filters into your Git repo.


---

Option 3 — Download tarball yourself and generate SHA512

If the asset tarball is in GitHub Releases, Bonsai, S3, or Artifactory, download it and calculate checksum:

curl -L -o asset_linux_arm64.tar.gz "<asset-tarball-url>"
sha512sum asset_linux_arm64.tar.gz

Then use the output in YAML:

- url: https://your-artifact-store/asset_linux_arm64.tar.gz
  sha512: <output-from-sha512sum>
  filters:
    - entity.system.os == 'linux'
    - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'

Sensu docs also show this packaging flow: create a .tar.gz, generate sha512sum, and host the tarball on a platform such as GitLab, Bitbucket, Artifactory, Apache, or NGINX. 

What to do now

Since your asset files do not have sha512, fix them before moving agents to ARM64.

Run:

grep -R "sha512" .
grep -R "url:" .
grep -R "arm64" .

Each ARM64 build should look like this:

- url: https://assets.bonsai.sensu.io/.../http-checks_<version>_linux_arm64.tar.gz
  sha512: <arm64-sha512>
  filters:
    - entity.system.os == 'linux'
    - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'

My recommendation

For your case:

Use Bonsai tarball URLs + SHA512 where available.
Mirror the tarballs to your internal S3/Artifactory if production reliability/security requires it.
Generate SHA512 yourself only for assets you build or mirror.

Do not leave sha512 blank. Sensu uses it to verify the asset before unpacking and running it.